Here are three impressive Swiss loco-monsters: the Ae 8/14 which
were built for heavy trains over the Gotthard line. For better curve
behaviour they had a special axle arrangement: the three central
axles could move sidewards in the frame and the first and last two
axles of each half were combined to special `Java trucks'. The locos
were technically and optically different from each other: the 11801
had a Buchli drive, the 11851 and 11852 had a Winterthur universal
drive. The 11852 was the most powerful locomotive of the world, it
was also lighter than the other two and had a more streamlined
carbody.

I just wrote this now in response to an email sent to me asking how
I did my ASCII artwork.  I responded by writing a brief walkthrough
of my thought processes (well, kind of) and just wanted to share
them on the group.  Let's see more people try to make create their
own new artwork instead of requesting for the old stuff all    
time.  It'll make for a better newsgroup overall and everyone w   
benefit!  -- Dan

Try practicing to make your own artwork by just typing on    
keyboard, which is what I do (I work just using the DOS text editor
which comes along with any MSDOS machine.  Any text editor will do.)
Begin by basic shapes.  For example, if you're making an animal -
say a giraffe - let's start with the head:

basically simple shapes to make it look approximately like it does
in real life (as best as you can, at least, in this case I've
cartooned it a bit :-) The " is making up the eyes, the . and , the
ears and a smile.  The i i are those antennae like things on top of
their heads (if I remember correctly).  I usually like to keep my
artwork within the size of a screen.  Since a giraffe is a t   
animal, I'm keeping the details smaller.  Then continue on with    
body and some legs.  Try to do a rough outline.

It's best to add some . and , in order to smooth out some of    
edges.  Then the tail is in the back.  Then add the detail - hair   
the neck and spots on the body.

That's pretty much for a quick giraffe that I just did while writ   
this letter.  You can add more stuff like a tree and a bird on a
branch too:

and it's cold/flu season, I thought I'd have a go at the entire vita

Pro-vitamins are precursors of vitamins that can be converted by the
body into the 'normal' vitamin. Beta-carotene is one of the most fam   
of these (yes, eating carrots *can* theoretically improve y   
night-vision), and is often used as a yellow/orange food colourant.

There are currently six numbered vitamins and two unnumbered vitamins   
this group. The complex of vitamins was discovered in yeast, and were
originally thought to be a single substance. Later, its constituents
were seperated and labelled. Further analysis showed that B's 4, 5, 7,
8, 9,           weren't vitamins, hence only 1, 2, 3, 5, 6, 12 remain,
plus biotin and folacin.

The carboxylic acid of nicotine, American officials called it 'niacin'
so as to prevent people thinking that they could fulfil their RDA   
this vitamin by smoking...

Pantothenic acid is another constituent of Coenzyme A, but nowadays
perhaps more famous are the numerous derivates collectively labelled as
"Pro-Vitamin B5 Complex" or panthenol/panthenate. These were originally
developed to help WWII burns victims, but it was somehow discovered at
the time that the complex helped to strengthen hair, and the f   
Pantene was set up (now owned by Glaxo Smithkline, info from SB's
website).

Verbose description: Vitamin B12 consists of:
a monovalent cobalt metal at the center, surrounded by a porphyrin-like
structure of tetrapyrrole rings, bound to the metal center is a cy   
group and a 5',6'-dimethylbenzimidazolyl nucleotide which is linked   
the tetrapyrrole rings via a phosphate sugar linkage.

Helps synthesise DNA, RNA, erythrocytes, and antibodies, so is essent   
in foetuses. Found in abundance in green leaves, but easily destroyed   
cooking.

Essential for the development of teeth and bones, plus the absorption   
calcium and phosphorous, vitamin D2 can be formed by the irradiation   
7-dehydrocholesterol (a derivative of cholesterol).
